article.headline: Pierce scores 24 in victory
article.linkText: Celtics hold off Wiz rally for second win in row
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Celtics didn't have Vin Baker, nor did they have much time to think about why Baker wasn't with them. After learning 45 minutes before tipoff that Baker had been suspended for noncompliance with his alcohol treatment program, the Celtics defeated the Washington Wizards 100-89 Friday night. It's the second time this season that Baker has been suspended. "I talked to the guys before the game and told them what the situation was," coach Jim O'Brien said. "We will discuss it more as a group tomorrow, but we're 45 minutes before a game and we need to concentrate on what we need to do to beat Washington." The Wizards, who trailed 78-59 at the end of the third quarter, used a 24-10 run sparked by seven points from Juan Dixon and six from Christian Laettner to pull to 88-83. "We tend to dig ourselves a hole and fight our way out of it," said Dixon, who scored 14 points. "The game wasn't over. We had plenty of time and guys played with a lot of energy and intensity." With the lead cut to five points, Celtics forward Paul Pierce, the game's leading scorer with 24 points, answered with a jumper. After a miss by Laettner, Ricky Davis hit a 3-pointer to give the Celtics a 93-83 lead. "We felt like we played poorly in the first half and we wanted to pick it up in the third -- get up on them and press them and pick up the tempo," Pierce said. The Celtics seemingly took control of the game in the second quarter after Kwame Brown hit a pair of free throws to give the Wizards a 33-32 lead. Walter McCarty's layup started a 32-7 run to give the Celtics a 64-40 lead. "It's too bad that we have to play so poorly to play so well," Wizards coach Eddie Jordan said. "That's not the mark of a winning team, quite frankly." Davis had 14 points for the Celtics. Mark Blount added 14 points and 14 rebounds, his second double-double of the season, and Jiri Welsch had 13 points. Steve Blake had a career-high 17 points for the Wizards. Larry Hughes added 15 and Dixon 14. Laettner had 13 points and 12 rebounds.

Game notes
Celtics rookie center Kendrick Perkins, who has scored seven points in two appearances this year, was activated from the injured list but did not play. ... Celtics center Chris Mihm missed his second straight game with a strained left hamstring. ... The Wizards are 7-21 overall and 2-14 on the road since losing shooting guard Gilbert Arenas to an abdominal strain. ... Celtics forward Jumaine Jones suffered a deep laceration of the lower lip in the third quarter that required nine stitches.
